sweet november
vanished into frosted air
and here's a real canadian winter attire: cabbage style🥶

The Christmas season has always been special to me. I decorated the house even during the pandemic when we weren't allowed to entertain.
Yet this year, with a pair of little feet stomping around, and tiny hands reaching for ornaments, I feel the marvels of December even stronger.

I believe that, although he won't remember this particular year, making it special can build up images in his subconscious, and establish his own perception of the world.

Hence, we fill it up with candlelight, pine scents, music, an advent calendar, and evening stories. We read Nativity, Christmas Carols, and old tales. To pass on an immune system, you know, against harsh winters he could face later in life. And memories of a warm, loving home—a little haven of Christmas for our boy🖤

curiosity shop

when I'm old and my photographs end up at a flea market (if them kids will even have some),
and I walk down the street with a roll of gift wrapping paper
hair as white as snow on the ground,
I would carry as many memories as possible to keep me company.
I spent too much of my time living
that there never was a turn for memories of past Christmases to approach,
find me all alone on a street, ready to talk.
and then when I remember 
there would be nothing else between flat roofs and stars, 
but raising steam and one more Christmas to live through
before gift paper and jewelry I got from my love
end up at a flea market.

Merry Christmas to your and your family! 
 ✨
At some point, Christmas movies and stories played a trick on our minds: "whatever heart desires will come true on Christmas Day". Not so much. Perhaps. In some cases. Of course, there is nothing wrong with a such noble intention to give people a sense of fairytale. Nothing wrong with a desire for a little miracle. 
 ✨
Throw a glance at the past year and it becomes perfectly clear why we all need Christmas. Besides being a transitional point where we sit down and release some pressure from continuous news round-ups, this day also offers a glimpse of hope. The hope of a greater miracle. Those Christmas stories, and movies we rewatch every year is only an attempt to reflect on the greatest miracle, to portray the loving spirit of this holiday.
 ✨
After all, Christmas is about light from above. One main miracle of incarnation that by its grandeur overcomes any other. Think about it, just because of Jesus’ birth we have Christmas. All that this celebration offers and signifies,—kindness, gift sharing, remembering those in need, and at least for one day learning to forgive each other's weaknesses and come together,—would not be possible if not for a newborn King, long ago in Bethlehem.

Happy Holidays!🖤✨

One day before the year ended
trees stood frosted.
Misleadingly bundled branches,
as if leaves came back again.
As if in the middle of winter, spring reappeared.
Not lost, but quietly faded, another year dissapeared.
Dissolving like snowflakes, numerous times and dates.
Laid gently like a fresh snow frost—
iced glossed a gleaming new day.
🤍

The beginning of a new year is always unstructured. Someone compared it to a fragile newborn baby. I say it is more like an ephemeral creature that is yet to become something of flesh and blood. It is neither beautiful nor ugly.
.
Have you ever woken up on January 1st, (then 5th) with a strange fog over your previously well-curated plans? Speaking of plans, they are not worth making, because this creature, a new year, still hangs somewhere between sky and ground, so indecisive about what it wants to become.
.
I know it is only a strange feeling that we put on one day. Or one week. Yet, I want to believe it has its place. Every life cycle has a right for renewal. Just like us. Isn’t it why we also feel so confused and even defenceless at the beginning of a new year? Here it is in the air, a new chance for some. Hope for the other. And we stand underneath this fog and do not know what to do with this creature. 
.
However, because it does not have any sense of frame yet, it offers one significant meaning (that is why we celebrate it too)—transformation. The idea is that if we only try hard, we can colour this unstructured creature, can teach it to be kind, and finally form it into a more pleasant period of our lives.

Amsterdam photo drop 1🤎

Amsterdam photo drop 2🤎
.
Amsterdam with its youthful business left a charming impression. Like a person who comes and fills up a house with his or her loud voice, entertaining ideas and a character of a romantic past and progressive future. Such an acquaintance does not become a close friend. But the memory of its vivid appearance stays. 
 .
So-called Venice of the North had a rather wet introduction. Over narrow canal houses—ghasts of wind and rain. 
Brick facades with their glorious past made me feel in the middle of a play. 
And even during our short visit, Amsterdam’s intimate, contradicting character of old and new revealed itself, reflected in the inhabitants of the city and waters of canals, one January evening.

Not that I didn’t know there is such a place where spring starts in January. An entry-level geography lesson can teach you so.
But knowing and being a part of it is where theory and experience differ.
Waking up to the world so green, as if it never was anything else, birdsongs through the open window, the scent of last year's leaves exposed and wet, sun-warmed soil, and first few blooms. I knew, of course, I knew. Yet today I found it out for myself🖤
.
.
.

Paris? It didn't disappoint. And how could it? 
Uniform-like buildings—a stage for a girl to feel like a main heroine of a story. Consistency of elegantly dressed people (in most cases) leaves room for my own style inspiration. 

Fashionable crowds and majestic churches.

Cafés and streets of Montmartre where great writers and artists wrote and discussed their ideas. 

Cashmere and perfume, extravagant old madames in fur on Champs-Élysées. 

The city has shown me all I’ve read about and even more. Effortless sophistication. The sophistication of art, architecture, demeanour of locals and atmosphere of cafés. How could I not love it?

I’ve heard a lot. I’ve heard how crowds of tourists could be utterly annoying, rats will be peeking out of every garbage can, and how overpriced and overrated Paris is. I’ve heard. I listened. I still wanted to make my own opinion of it.
I’m not saying it all doesn’t exist. But putting away impressions and high expectations about Paris that cinema created in minds of millions, I still believed this place had something special to offer.

So it has. It truly is special. Unique even. The center of all things fine. In fact, Paris is a Merry-Go-Round in disguise. Hop on a wooden, gold-decorated horse, there is space for everyone!🖤

P.S. The best part is, my husband who was quite skeptical about going to Paris, loved it to pieces.

Jardin du Luxembourg’s fountain saw us 
kissing each other, just like many others, 
the water never dried out, 
people continued kissing.
When they were no more, water kept running, 
but they
turned into kissing statues—
someone watched how love 
conquered time,
and set hearts in marble stone:
so hearts could keep loving, 
meanwhile the stone faded, thinned out or 
let on some moss.
Make statue of our love, 
so when we are no more,
there would be at least one kiss left
by the fountain in Jardin du Luxembourg.

Art is marriage and marriage is art. 

Whoever is involved in any artistic process or relationship would know what I’m talking about. 

In both life consists of certain episodes. 
One—I’m devotedly working and committing myself to you. 
Two—I feel like a fraud, and the sense of belonging and connection is vanishing. 
Three—I’m angry, so angry I promise to never get involved again. 
Four—no inspiration, but comfortable coexistence. 
Five—nothing else in life matters more than this. 

I know you are there. You know I am there, and that is more than enough to get through the day. (Think the same of any artistic path you choose.) These are the days when I look at you and a strange warmth spreads up from head to toe. It squeezes the heart and causes tears because of gratitude for a loving being nearby. It fills up the room with tenderness. 

And I know, and you know that to experience as many of such days as possible is to commit fully. Nothing else but love and devotion, the choice you and I make day after day, (whether to your art or your spouse) moves the process🖤

📷: @olyashendrik

New blog post: Paris Impressions🖤(link is in the bio)

"We returned to Canada, but I kept reliving Paris every time I told stories to friends and family. One of those friends noticed that I brought back a previously unrecognized glow. I thought, perhaps, as my husband noted, it was because there I was ‘in my element’. I do not find it strange that, just like with certain people, only a few places in the world can open up the heart of one specific person. Do you know what I mean? Paris is not for everyone. 

I am not being snobbish here. Yet, I have heard a lot of disappointing remarks about this city. From people who were vivid travellers and people who left their hometown for the first time. People who travelled there during spring and autumn, and still did not find any charm, but labeled every aspect of it as ‘overrated’. There are places for people like that as well, places that will teach them something significant, a memory they will take back and never let go. Even if Paris was not such a place for those people, it, however, became consequential for me."

Hard to believe winter would ever be over
meant to pass, it lingers.

We hide in art galleries where spring 
at least was captured in past centuries:
birds move as brush strokes 
and sky clears slowly,
dark circles around trees' stems enlarge.
Those artists surely saw it coming,
meanwhile I did not.

If I would investigate the timidness of thoughts, 
(they sleep covered underneath cracking frost),
I would conveniently use winter months to blame. 

The day art galleries would let us out,
skies are painted blue and pink,
branches nets, still transparent,
only background changes,
the air steering in between—brings dripping thawing.

The same repeats each year,
I’m loosing hope, 
spring’s thrusting through.

I am never signing up for the type of feminism that proclaims misandry. But, I will speak up against systems where women are treated as property without any respect or decency. 
You know, the main issue a modern woman faces (at least in western cultures) is a push on her to be equal to men. When if fact, it is not so. It never will be so. I am not talking about the right to vote, pursue your dreams or ask for higher pay. That all should be common sense. 
I am talking about a natural, core of existence, difference. Women are different biologically and psychologically. They are made differently. The point is to admit it, and finally embrace it. 

I do not want to find myself ashamed for feeling proud of being a woman. Every day women I meet reveal endurance, grace, kindness, and knowledge that many men are not capable of having. How is that not wonderful? 
Surely, post-modernist society can say a lot of things about how disproportionate, and unfair it is to be a woman in its original sense. I, however, think that we, people, create that society. And only by embracing femininity, enjoying every role that women were given,—be it sacrificial love of a mother to a sick child, a devoted wife, a passionate career-driven woman, a single one, a widow, a grandmother or a little girl in search of her path,—we could change that destructive movement.

I want to learn to take every season with acceptance not rooted in blame. Especially in self-blame for not being productive (read, fruitful) in wintertime. It is also not an excuse for sitting and hoping for an easy change. Just a realization that directing my energy towards slow, simple activities and pleasures will one day pay off with better results than forced attempts to complete some creative quota. 

I can’t really say, I might be in the minority of those underachievers. Maybe I’m not using all the potential of a period of stagnation (which typically happens once a year). Yet, I made a deal with myself, that if today, (or even a week later), I’m still in this stage collecting ideas, resting and simply existing, drinking my coffee, waiting for spring, looking at the mountains, waiting for blooming inspiration to reappear, that is okay with me.

•

Write down: J-u-l-y
watch how blood red sun
drips down trees branches.
When picking strawberries squish a few
let juice dry out, stain you like perfume and 
oil paint.
Swim in any clear water you find
even if sunset chill would take a while to fully dry your body and shivering mind.
Then flowers, we can’t forget fresh flowers:
July—days of many wild flowers.
While trains whizzle, swallowing up overheating people,
(as per Brodsky: the heat has reached the blinding point where 
an airplane looks like a butterfly in sizzling sky),
sunsets swallow up high summer.
And all you have to do is run along it 
run to touch the berry stained hand of this month
until there is no more.
Write down: g-o-n-e.

“The older one becomes the more love adjoined with sadness one is capable of feeling.”

Children, for instance, are quite radical. They don’t know of hues and levels of emotions, they take it as either good or bad, black or white, love or hate, laugh or cry. Which is alright. 
The discovery of other colours between black and white comes later, you don’t even notice when and what exactly transforms you. But one day, you find out that grief and sadness accompany love. With every act of kindness you hear of more evil out there in the world. Sickness balances out an attempt to stay fit and healthy. Homelessness and luxury. Friends getting married and friends getting divorced. Unexpected deaths and the necessity to move on.

Unlike a child who deals with one issue and one emotion at a time, (and forgets about it as soon as some other experience comes his way), you have to deal with the whole batch. And really, there are only two ways to live with that—observe it and be affected by it when necessary, or numb it.

Instead, I’m leaving pieces of my heart with 

people 

places 

street corners 

near paintings which make some cry

with music floating in the air 

by the fountain 

and blushing maples.

So when I’m back they would be proofs of love’s existence 
Not perfect 
but alive.

Seasonal. 

They call it crispy because overnight everything turns as such. Fragile leaves that crumble and rot and smell like tart spices or cigars. Crunchy-crunchy. 

The sound a horse makes cracking an apple, a crispy apple.

Air that is transparent and thick at the same time. It is also sweet, and the sweetness of it is in cinnamon, honey and late chrysanthemums. If you move your hand through the air too fast it will crumble, like a thin glass or sugar coating on creme brulee. 

I walk down the street and in between buildings that feel so fragile, wrapped in that autumnal air, as if made of paper. As if one blow of wind and with a crackling noise they will crumble. 

Must be because everything is slowly drying out. 

Must be because we are surprisingly intervened with nature, and just like skin cells regenerate more slowly with age, leading to thinning and fragility and dryness, so does autumn. So does the end of the year🍁

29🥳
(aesthetics of a dreamy stay at the rockies and some birthday thoughts)🤍

When I was growing up there were many of them around me, cousins in their thirties. And I thought they were not only at a certain age, but the ‘I’ve-got-it-all-figured-out’ benchmark. In my observation, they had everything they dreamt of when they were sixteen. 

Now, as I am just one year away from the age that I naively hoped would bring clarity and success, I know that nobody has it completely figured out. 

Some think they are still too far from where they hoped to be by their thirties and feel like they failed their childhood promises to themselves. Others are on the verge of figuring out a new role in their family or career and there are days of complete dissatisfaction too. There are also those who took traumas of the past and let it affect or transform their thirties.
I know them, they are among my friends and relatives, and they are those who I mistakenly thought figured it all out. 

So here I am, not figuring it all out, yet realizing I don’t even need to do that. Never had to. Should have never expected it of myself. Maybe all I have to do is to figure out how to live one single day. How to do my best and love my strongest today. Then the next day, and the one to come. 
Maybe all I should expect of myself is to accept and enjoy the energy, confusion, solutions and dreams this age brings.

was hardwired to admire something great,
beyond abilities and full understanding.

of making us feel happier,

Admiration so powerful it breaks through hard shells of disinterest, routine, disasters. 
By something great they meant acts of kindness, 
the way we connect with one another,
mountains, of course,
overall nature with its imperfect curvy lines.
God. 
Art.
A human’s body and life in it.
I could keep on going on, but you could go ahead and read that study.
I only know that once you’ve started 
there always will be urge for more
greatness.

I’m collecting Christmas memories like sparkling, fragile, glass ornaments, both modest and extravagant. I can’t do otherwise. If I stop collecting them, all the ornaments from previous years would lose their meaning, left stacked somewhere in the basement. 
Of course, Christmas is more than treasured memories, I know that. This is not the point. 
•
Back in childhood, you had to do absolutely nothing but be there for wonders of the season. It was wonderful by default. It was wonderful because your mom or dad or someone who loved you created a stage for celebration right in front of your eyes. 
(I had the most stunning pink velvet dress for the school Christmas play because my mom spent the night before sewing it. Of course, I stumbled over its length, but I was quite a fairy.) 

Then you grow up and start searching and questioning whether it is you who is no longer capable of feeling the ‘spirit of Christmas’ or it never was a big deal to begin with. 
Because neither answer satisfies you, you decide to start anew. You collect, create and participate in special events only to feel the glimpse of Christmas you used to know as a child. 
•
I’m not sure yet if I do enough to create festive, memorable days for my kid. Still, I want to believe that when we cuddle underneath the blanket to read the Nativity story and Christmas classics, when he asks for Silent Night before falling asleep, I’m doing something right. I'm opening the door to him into this marvellous time of the year. As if through those moments I take him by the hand and lead him towards collecting his own shining memories🖤

film by @olyashendrik and some poetry from archives🖤

Could I build a road through a rugged forest,
so thick, to cut it with a saw would take me a decade?
Would I still admire majestic mountains,
take them as they were,
even if their wilderness wouldn’t spare me from frosted fingers?
Would muse come walking down that hill
so I could write poetry about snowcapped peaks
or would I search for comfort, and nothing more?
I know myself, I would have left long time ago
and wait for someone else to cut through stone.
Yet, here I am, with tools to build my own road.
And no one else.

—Pioneers in the Rockies
